## 5. Architecture FAQ (Why these choices?)

### Q: Why do we have WebSockets if we use MQTT? (Update: We don't!)

- **Correction**: You are right. The current codebase _has_ WebSocket code ([TelemetryGateway](file:///d:/Users/chellakkumar/D-Documents/Enarxi/GBI/Air%20Quality%20Monitor/gbi-backend/src/realtime/telemetry.gateway.ts#13-92)), but since your architecture is **HTTP Polling (Telemetry) + SSE (Notifications)**, the WebSocket code is "zombie code".
- **Action**: We will **delete** [TelemetryGateway](file:///d:/Users/chellakkumar/D-Documents/Enarxi/GBI/Air%20Quality%20Monitor/gbi-backend/src/realtime/telemetry.gateway.ts#13-92) to save RAM and avoid confusion.
- **New Flow**:
  - **Telemetry**: Device -> MQTT -> DB. Frontend -> Polls API every 1 min.
  - **Alerts**: Backend -> SSE -> Frontend (Immediate push).

### Q: Why Mosquitto instead of EMQX?

- **Resource Constraint**: You have a **$12 Droplet (2GB RAM)**.
  - **EMQX**: Requires ~200MB+ RAM just to start and spikes higher under load. It runs on the Erlang VM, which is heavy for a small shared instance.
  - **Mosquitto**: Ultra-lightweight (C-based). Uses ~5MB RAM.
- **Compatibility**: Your code uses standard MQTT via the `mqtt.js` library. It does **not** use any proprietary EMQX features (like Rule Engine or Shared Subscriptions).
- **Upgrade Path**: If you upgrade the server to 4GB+ RAM later, you can swap Mosquitto for EMQX without changing a single line of code.
